  ],
  "theory": "A single-phase transformer transfers AC electrical energy between two circuits through electromagnetic induction. It consists of a primary winding (N1 turns), secondary winding (N2 turns), and an iron core. When AC voltage V1 is applied to the primary, it sets up an alternating flux Φ in the core. This flux links with the secondary winding and induces EMF. EMF equation: E1 = 4.44 × f × N1 × Φm (primary) and E2 = 4.44 × f × N2 × Φm (secondary). Turns ratio: V1/V2 = N1/N2. Losses: Core losses (hysteresis + eddy current) and Copper losses (I²R in windings). Efficiency η = Pout/Pin × 100%.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "EMF equation: E = 4.44 × f × N × Φmax (RMS value)",
    "Turns ratio: a = N1/N2 = V1/V2 = I2/I1",
    "Core losses: Hysteresis loss (∝ f × Bm^1.6) + Eddy current loss (∝ f² × Bm²)",
    "Copper losses: PCu = I1²R1 + I2²R2 (resistance losses in windings)",
    "Efficiency η = V2I2cosφ2 / (V2I2cosφ2 + core losses + copper losses)"
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "Step-up/step-down voltage in power distribution systems",
    "Electrical isolation between circuits for safety",
    "Impedance matching in audio and communication circuits"
  ]
